<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Just add some limit free zones</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?TheBlack[BCK]">TheBlack[BCK]</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 1:34 p.m. 9/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Just add some limit free zones<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=350" TARGET=_self>Level Limit Applications and Problems</A> (The RealmWeaver)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>

<BR>Add a zone or two that ignore the level limit, and use +/-4 for the rest of the game areas.
<P>For smaller groups, a /gduel feature would be nice. Otherwise some calculation of group ability or total level is needed as mentioned.
<P>&gt; Level limits are probably one of the most promising topics being
<BR>&gt; discussed/considered at the current time. However, the input I
<BR>&gt; have gathered from posters on this forum and elsewhere leads me
<BR>&gt; to believe that there is a problem inherent in imposing level
<BR>&gt; limit restrictions in EverQuest. The headache of grouping
<BR>&gt; calculations have been discussed already, and the problem raised
<BR>&gt; by large groups where some players are "in range"
<BR>&gt; while others are out, etc.
<P>&gt; I believe this problem originates from an unbalance in the power
<BR>&gt; increase of in EverQuest's level system; in order to impose a
<BR>&gt; system of level limits, it is almost a necessity to have a
<BR>&gt; balanced power-gauge so each limit can be arithmetically derived
<BR>&gt; instead of just using guesswork.
<P>&gt; In other words, if the levels were balanced as far as power is
<BR>&gt; concerned, we could simply impose a +- 5 level limit, and impose
<BR>&gt; it on the sum of group levels as well. In other words, a group
<BR>&gt; of two level 10s could be challegend by a 15-25. A group of
<BR>&gt; three level 10s could face a 25-35, etc. For this to work,
<BR>&gt; however, the sum power of two level 10s must be rougly equal to
<BR>&gt; a level 20. As far as I have heard and read, this is not the
<BR>&gt; case. So we must be wary when imposing level limits of a static
<BR>&gt; size on an unbalanced system. Will the fight between a level 50
<BR>&gt; and 45 be as evenly matched as between a 20 and 15, or 10 and 5?
<BR>&gt; Will a group of 3 tens be subject to the wrath of a 30? If so,
<BR>&gt; how will they fare?
<P>&gt; At any rate, what I am warning against is focusing too much on
<BR>&gt; the numbers and not enough on the actual power of a player of
<BR>&gt; that level. A balance must be reached before any restrictions
<BR>&gt; can be effectively imposed.
<P>&gt; The RealmWeaver
<BR>&gt; dcc5500@rit.edu
<BR>&gt; ICQ: 30795819
<BR>&gt; IM: WrldWeaver
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
